Captain.

465
00:37:59,957 --> 00:38:05,588
Captain has asked me to brief you on the
emergency action message we received.

466
00:38:06,589 --> 00:38:09,342
As you know, before we got underway,

467
00:38:09,425 --> 00:38:13,512
the Russian army was in position
encircling the rebel camps,

468
00:38:13,596 --> 00:38:18,100
and Radchenko started making threats
should anyone move in on him,

469
00:38:18,184 --> 00:38:23,606
that he would launch his land-based
nuclear weapons at the US and at Japan.

470
00:38:23,689 --> 00:38:28,402
The safeguard was that the Russian
government controlled the launch codes.

471
00:38:28,527 --> 00:38:32,990
Intel now indicates that those
launch codes have been compromised,

472
00:38:33,115 --> 00:38:36,869
and US military forces have been
directed to set DEFCON three.

473
00:38:36,953 --> 00:38:40,414
The last time we hit this state of emergency
was 32½ years ago,

474
00:38:40,498 --> 00:38:43,918
during the Cuban missile crisis.

475
00:38:44,001 --> 00:38:48,130
So this is what it's all about, gentlemen.
It's what we train for.

476
00:38:48,214 --> 00:38:51,342
It's why this ship was built.

477
00:38:51,425 --> 00:38:55,930
And it's what our nuclear weapons
will be used for if necessary.

478
00:38:56,389 --> 00:38:58,474
Captain.

479
00:38:58,891 --> 00:39:02,019
The NCA has determined that

480
00:39:02,103 --> 00:39:07,108
should our satellites detect
rebel missiles being fueled -

481
00:39:07,233 --> 00:39:11,153
which means they could be
launched in just over one hour -

482
00:39:11,237 --> 00:39:13,823
we'll be compelled to act.

483
00:39:16,075 --> 00:39:20,037
Now, given our patrol sector
here in the Emperor Sea Mounts,

484
00:39:20,121 --> 00:39:23,916
it seems clear that our friends
in the Pentagon

485
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:28,296
are setting us up for
a potential preemptive strike.

486
00:39:28,379 --> 00:39:31,299
It's important to remain focused.

487
00:39:32,925 --> 00:39:36,012
Keep your men informed.

488
00:39:39,724 --> 00:39:41,809
Any questions?

489
00:39:44,312 --> 00:39:46,939
Dismissed.

490
00:39:53,988 --> 00:39:55,906
We lost that frying unit and then...

491
00:40:04,415 --> 00:40:06,834
I'm gonna fuck you up!
Get out! Get...

492
00:40:06,917 --> 00:40:10,046
Get out of here, man! Get him out!
Motherfucker!

493
00:40:10,838 --> 00:40:12,798
Fuckin' Guinea piece of shit.

494
00:40:17,511 --> 00:40:21,349
- Rivetti, what's up?
- I'm sorry, sir. Just a difference of opinion.

495
00:40:21,432 --> 00:40:24,977
- What about?
- It's too silly, sir. I'd rather just forget...

496
00:40:25,061 --> 00:40:29,565
I don't give a damn about what you'd rather
forget about. Why were you two fighting?

497
00:40:29,649 --> 00:40:32,943
I said the Kirby Silver Surfer
was the only real Silver Surfer,

498
00:40:33,027 --> 00:40:37,823
and that the Moebius Silver Surfer was
shit. Bennefield's a big Moebius fan, and...

499
00:40:37,907 --> 00:40:42,370
Things got out of hand. I pushed him, he
pushed me. I lost my head, sir. I'm sorry.

500
00:40:42,411 --> 00:40:44,914
Rivetti, you're a supervisor.

501
00:40:45,039 --> 00:40:47,375
You can get a commission like that.

502
00:40:47,458 --> 00:40:50,002
I know it, sir. You're 100% right.

503
00:40:50,127 --> 00:40:52,588
- It'll never happen again.
- It better not.

504
00:40:52,672 --> 00:40:55,758
I see this kind of nonsense,
I'll write you up. Understand?

505
00:40:55,841 --> 00:40:57,093
- Understand?
- Yes, sir.

506
00:40:57,176 --> 00:40:59,595
You set an example
even in the face of stupidity.

507
00:40:59,679 --> 00:41:02,556
Every comic book reader
knows that Kirby Silver Surfer

508
00:41:02,640 --> 00:41:05,643
is the only true Silver Surfer.
Now, am I right or wrong?

509
00:41:05,726 --> 00:41:08,729
- You're right, sir.
- All right. Get out of here.

510
00:41:30,126 --> 00:41:31,502
Captain.

511
00:41:31,585 --> 00:41:36,132
- How can I help you?
- Test results from the missile drill.

512
00:41:40,720 --> 00:41:42,680
This the best they can do?

513
00:41:42,805 --> 00:41:46,183
- No, sir, but that's what they did.
- I want this down to five minutes.

514
00:41:46,309 --> 00:41:48,352
- Train on it.
- Yes, sir.

515
00:41:48,477 --> 00:41:52,273
Tell your buddy Weps
we're gonna do it again.

516
00:41:52,356 --> 00:41:55,318
We're gonna keep on doin' it
until he gets it right.

517
00:41:55,401 --> 00:41:57,695
Damn.

518
00:41:57,737 --> 00:42:01,574
Feels like the whole crew
needs a kick in the ass.

519
00:42:01,657 --> 00:42:04,035
Or a pat on the back, sir.

520
00:42:04,118 --> 00:42:07,455
I just witnessed a fight down in
crew's mess. No big deal, but...

521
00:42:07,538 --> 00:42:12,627
I think the men are... a little on edge
with all we're going through.

522
00:42:12,710 --> 00:42:15,087
Morale seems to be a bit low.

523
00:42:17,423 --> 00:42:21,594
Well, you seem to have
the pulse of the men.

524
00:42:24,180 --> 00:42:26,807
Thank you, sir.

525
00:42:35,483 --> 00:42:36,484
Attention, please.

526
00:42:39,487 --> 00:42:43,074
Mr. Hunter has brought it
to my attention

527
00:42:43,157 --> 00:42:47,578
that morale may be a bit low.

528
00:42:47,620 --> 00:42:50,414
That you may be a bit...

529
00:42:50,915 --> 00:42:52,416
On edge, sir.

530
00:42:52,500 --> 00:42:54,585
...on edge.

531
00:42:55,670 --> 00:42:58,005
So I suggest this,

532
00:42:58,089 --> 00:43:01,842
any crew member who feels
he can't handle the situation

533
00:43:01,926 --> 00:43:04,637
can leave the ship right now.

534
00:43:05,304 --> 00:43:09,642
Gentlemen, we're at DEFCON three.
War is imminent.

535
00:43:10,810 --> 00:43:12,436
<i>This is the captain.</i>

536
00:43:14,313 --> 00:43:16,399
That is all.

537
00:43:19,485 --> 00:43:22,071
Very inspiring, sir.

538
00:43:24,115 --> 00:43:26,450
Come on, Bear.
Come on. Come on.

539
00:43:39,213 --> 00:43:41,173
Come in.

540
00:43:41,257 --> 00:43:43,092
Sir.

541
00:43:47,972 --> 00:43:51,684
Cob, this is a difficult subject
to talk about. Uh...

542
00:43:53,102 --> 00:43:56,314
- I gather from...
- Maybe I can help, sir.

543
00:43:56,397 --> 00:43:59,567
I know I'm overweight,
but this is my last tour.

544
00:43:59,692 --> 00:44:01,902
I retire after this.

545
00:44:02,028 --> 00:44:05,656
I just... can't seem to stop eating.

546
00:44:12,246 --> 00:44:15,291
- Have a seat, Cob.
- Yes, sir.

547
00:44:17,543 --> 00:44:19,795
What did you think of
the captain's speech?

548
00:44:19,879 --> 00:44:25,259
Well, the captain seems to know
what his men seem to need.

549
00:44:25,343 --> 00:44:27,178
A pat on the back or a kick in the ass?

550
00:44:27,219 --> 00:44:30,056
His speech made sense to me.

551
00:44:30,139 --> 00:44:32,516
So why don't you say
what's really on your mind?

552
00:44:32,600 --> 00:44:36,103
With all due respect, this thing between
you and the captain is no good.

553
00:44:36,228 --> 00:44:40,024
Somebody's gotta bend, sir,
and he is the skipper.

554
00:44:40,107 --> 00:44:42,193
I'm aware of that, Cob.

555
00:44:42,276 --> 00:44:44,487
Yes, sir.

556
00:44:46,739 --> 00:44:51,327
Sir, what I think we have here is
a difference in management styles.

557
00:44:51,410 --> 00:44:54,413
But as unpredictable as he is,
there is a logic to it.

558
00:44:54,497 --> 00:44:57,875
He navigates by his own star,
not many men can do that.

559
00:44:57,959 --> 00:45:02,088
Cob's rules of navy leadership.
One, look like you know what you're doing.

560
00:45:02,171 --> 00:45:04,715
Two, the men must believe you
know what you're doing.

561
00:45:04,799 --> 00:45:07,259
And three, and most important,

562
00:45:07,301 --> 00:45:11,889
everybody's got an opinion
but the captain's gotta make a choice.

563
00:45:11,973 --> 00:45:16,727
You live and die with that, and that's where
the skipper's earned his stripes, sir.

564
00:45:16,769 --> 00:45:20,481
I've seen it time and time again.

565
00:45:22,274 --> 00:45:24,402
So when you're right, you're right.

566
00:45:24,485 --> 00:45:28,990
That's what my daddy said.
Right's right, and wrong's for nobody.

567
00:45:30,700 --> 00:45:32,576
You hungry?

568
00:45:32,618 --> 00:45:34,620
Always.

569
00:45:35,621 --> 00:45:37,623
Let's get something to eat.

570
00:45:37,707 --> 00:45:39,792
Yes, sir.

571
00:45:48,926 --> 00:45:52,096
Sup? Come here.

572
00:45:53,055 --> 00:45:56,559
You hear that?

573
00:45:56,642 --> 00:46:03,482
I've got a broadband contact bearing 0-4-7.
Assigning tracker Sierra in ATF.

574
00:46:03,524 --> 00:46:07,737
Conn, Sonar. We have a possible
submerged submarine bearing 0-4-7.

575
00:46:07,820 --> 00:46:10,114
Designate contact Master 2-8.

576
00:46:10,197 --> 00:46:14,035
Sonar, Conn, aye. Man battle stations
torpedo. Rig for ultraquiet.

577
00:46:14,118 --> 00:46:17,663
- Make tubes one and four fully ready.
- Tubes one and four fully ready. Aye.

578
00:46:20,750 --> 00:46:22,668
<i> Man battle stations torpedo.</i>

579
00:46:27,923 --> 00:46:29,300
What do you got?

580
00:46:29,342 --> 00:46:33,679
Sir, a possible submerged submarine,
bearing 0-4-9, designate Master 2-8.

581
00:46:34,847 --> 00:46:40,436
Best depth for evasion, sir,
is 8-3-1 feet to avoid that sub.

582
00:46:40,519 --> 00:46:43,648
Mahoney, this is the captain.
Increase your speed to standard.

583
00:46:43,731 --> 00:46:45,983
Come left to course 2-7-0.

584
00:46:46,108 --> 00:46:49,528
Make your depth 8-3-1 feet, smartly.

585
00:46:51,697 --> 00:46:54,200
- You find out who that is.
- Aye, sir.

586
00:46:55,701 --> 00:46:57,620
Who are you, sweetheart?

587
00:46:57,703 --> 00:47:01,999
Helm, all ahead standard.
Dive, make your depth 8-3-1 feet, smartly.

588
00:47:02,083 --> 00:47:03,084
Aye, sir.

589
00:47:10,925 --> 00:47:15,262
Conn, Radio. Receiving emergency
action message. Recommend alert one.

590
00:47:15,346 --> 00:47:16,889
Recommend alert one.

591
00:47:17,014 --> 00:47:20,017
<i> Alert one. Alert one.
Incoming emergency action message.</i>

592
00:47:28,859 --> 00:47:32,113
Captain, we have a properly formatted
emergency action message

593
00:47:32,196 --> 00:47:35,700
from National Command Authority
for strategic missile launch.

594
00:47:35,783 --> 00:47:38,536
- I concur, sir.
- Get the authenticator.

595
00:47:59,765 --> 00:48:02,810
Chief of the Watch,
secure for battle stations torpedo.

596
00:48:02,893 --> 00:48:05,771
Man battle stations missile
for strategic launch.

597
00:48:05,813 --> 00:48:07,815
Secure for battle stations torpedo.

598
00:48:07,898 --> 00:48:11,193
- Man battle stations missile...
- Permission to authenticate.

599
00:48:11,277 --> 00:48:13,571
Permission granted. Authenticate.

600
00:48:17,658 --> 00:48:20,119
"Bravo, Echo, Echo,

601
00:48:20,161 --> 00:48:24,123
Charlie, Alpha, Tango, Alpha."

602
00:48:24,206 --> 00:48:27,501
"Bravo, Echo, Echo, Charlie,

603
00:48:27,627 --> 00:48:31,088
Alpha, Tango, Alpha."

604
00:48:33,382 --> 00:48:35,843
- Message is authentic, sir.
- I concur, sir.

605
00:48:35,926 --> 00:48:37,470
I concur, sir.

606
00:48:39,096 --> 00:48:43,434
- Message is authentic.
- Sir, your captain's missile key.

607
00:48:53,027 --> 00:48:58,240
This is the captain. Set condition One SQ
for strategic missile launch.

608
00:48:58,324 --> 00:49:01,744
<i>Spin up missiles one through five
and 20 through 24.</i>

609
00:49:01,827 --> 00:49:05,122
<i>The release of nuclear weapons
has been authorized.</i>

610
00:49:07,291 --> 00:49:09,251
<i>This is not a drill.</i>

611
00:49:12,672 --> 00:49:16,801
XO, take the conn. I'm going
to my stateroom for the launch keys.

612
00:49:16,884 --> 00:49:19,011
XO has the conn.

613
00:49:24,684 --> 00:49:27,979
Set condition One SQ
for strategic missile launch.

614
00:49:28,521 --> 00:49:32,274
<i>Spin up missiles one through five,
20 through 24.</i>

615
00:49:33,484 --> 00:49:37,613
<i>The release of nuclear weapons
has been authorized. This is the XO.</i>

616
00:49:37,697 --> 00:49:44,620
Conn, Weapons. Estimated time to One
SQ for strategic launch is 14 minutes, sir.

617
00:49:53,546 --> 00:49:56,716
One, two, three, four, five, six.

618
00:49:56,799 --> 00:49:58,843
Go, sailor, go.

619
00:50:02,221 --> 00:50:06,434
<i> Set condition One SQ
for strategic missile launch.</i>

620
00:50:06,517 --> 00:50:09,520
<i>- Comin' through!
- Spin up missiles one through five</i>

621
00:50:09,603 --> 00:50:11,105
<i>and 20 through 24.</i>

622
00:50:22,617 --> 00:50:25,369
- I have the conn.
- The captain has the conn.

623
00:50:25,453 --> 00:50:28,956
Passing 5-5-0 feet.

624
00:50:34,128 --> 00:50:38,257
Conn, Radio. Sir, we're out of VLF radio
range. Full message capacity is cut off.

625
00:50:38,341 --> 00:50:41,218
Radio, Conn.
Extend extremely low frequency antenna.

626
00:50:41,302 --> 00:50:44,305
Passing 600 feet.
Coming to 8-3-1 feet, sir.

627
00:50:54,982 --> 00:50:57,985
Jesus. Oh, God. Uh...

628
00:50:58,069 --> 00:51:01,405
Conn, Sonar.
Uh, sir, we have his classification.

629
00:51:03,032 --> 00:51:05,910
Mark that tape.
Get the classification on your monitor.

630
00:51:05,952 --> 00:51:07,453
What the hell is going on?

631
00:51:07,536 --> 00:51:11,624
Sir, the Master 2-8 is classified as
a Russian Akula class hunter-killer.

632
00:51:11,707 --> 00:51:15,628
Bearing 1-9-6, sir. He's close,
but I don't think he's spotted us.

633
00:51:21,217 --> 00:51:23,219
- Stay on him!
- Aye, sir.

634
00:51:23,302 --> 00:51:27,473
- Captain has the conn.
- Passing 800 feet, sir.

635
00:51:27,556 --> 00:51:30,351
Continue to dive.
Give me five degree down bubble.

636
00:51:30,434 --> 00:51:33,354
- Continue rigging for ultraquiet.
- Aye, aye, sir.

637
00:51:33,437 --> 00:51:37,984
Five degree down bubble.
Rigging for ultraquiet, sir.

638
00:51:52,665 --> 00:51:55,167
Gentlemen, this is the captain.

639
00:51:55,209 --> 00:51:58,045
We have an Akula class submarine
out there.

640
00:51:58,129 --> 00:52:02,466
<i>We know Radchenko controls at least
four submarines. This could be one.</i>

641
00:52:02,508 --> 00:52:06,262
<i>Russian rebels have threatened
to launch against our country,</i>

642
00:52:06,345 --> 00:52:08,222
<i>and are fueling right now.</i>

643
00:52:08,306 --> 00:52:12,268
<i>They will have launch capability
in 60 minutes.</i>

644
00:52:12,351 --> 00:52:16,981
<i>We have orders to launch our missiles,
which is exactly what we're going to do.</i>

645
00:52:17,106 --> 00:52:20,359
<i>We are rigging for ultraquiet.
All hands, be ready.</i>

646
00:52:21,027 --> 00:52:23,321
<i>This is as real as it gets.</i>

647
00:52:23,362 --> 00:52:27,491
<i>We'll presume nothing,
defend ourselves at all cost.</i>

648
00:52:27,575 --> 00:52:33,581
If that sub so much as comes around
or opens up a tube door, we'll take her out.

649
00:52:35,041 --> 00:52:36,792
Passing 900 feet.

650
00:52:44,717 --> 00:52:46,344
He's gone.

651
00:52:46,427 --> 00:52:48,929
Like hell he is.

652
00:52:49,013 --> 00:52:50,431
He's up there.

653
00:52:50,514 --> 00:52:52,224
9-5-0.

654
00:52:52,308 --> 00:52:57,021
Conn, Weapons. Missile systems
ready to launch in 11 minutes.

655
00:53:07,490 --> 00:53:12,119
Conn, Radio. Receiving transmission
on extremely low frequency receiver, sir.

656
00:53:12,203 --> 00:53:15,164
Very well.
Mr. Hunter, go to Radio, please.

657
00:53:17,959 --> 00:53:20,127
- OK, pull up the code.
- What do you got?

658
00:53:20,211 --> 00:53:24,757
XO, incoming EAM, but we're too deep
to receive any radio communication, sir.

659
00:53:31,430 --> 00:53:32,890
<i>- Captain.
- XO.</i>

660
00:53:32,974 --> 00:53:36,435
<i>We got a limited radio transmission
indicating an incoming EAM.</i>

661
00:53:36,560 --> 00:53:39,522
<i>We need to go shallow
to reestablish communications.</i>

662
00:53:39,605 --> 00:53:44,235
With that sub still up there?
Mr. Hunter, it's my inten...

663
00:53:44,318 --> 00:53:46,529
<i>- Come up to Conn, Mr. Hunter.
- Yes, sir.</i>

664
00:53:48,155 --> 00:53:50,366
- Zero bubble.
- Zero bubble. Aye, sir.

665
00:53:50,449 --> 00:53:52,368
1275 feet, sir.

666
00:53:59,125 --> 00:54:04,005
<i> Conn. Weapons. Missile systems
ready to launch in ten minutes.</i>

667
00:54:04,088 --> 00:54:06,215
<i>- Sir.
- Attention, all hands.</i>

668
00:54:06,299 --> 00:54:09,093
<i>- Ship has been rigged for ultraquiet.
- Captain?</i>

669
00:54:15,099 --> 00:54:19,895
When our missile system is ready,
Mr. Hunter,

670
00:54:19,979 --> 00:54:22,940
it is my intention
to rise to launch depth,

671
00:54:23,024 --> 00:54:27,820
launch our birds and then get
the hell out of there. Not until then.

672
00:54:27,903 --> 00:54:30,948
I can't jeopardize
the safety of this ship.

673
00:54:31,032 --> 00:54:33,784
Yes, sir.

674
00:54:33,868 --> 00:54:37,371
May I suggest that we float the buoy, sir?
We have enough cable.

675
00:54:37,496 --> 00:54:42,293
That should give us enough reach
to receive the EAM transmission. Sir.

676
00:54:44,378 --> 00:54:48,132
Very well, float the buoy.

677
00:54:48,174 --> 00:54:52,803
- Chief of the Watch, float the buoy.
- Float the radio buoy. Aye, sir.

678
00:55:00,144 --> 00:55:04,523
Radio buoy
deploying, sir. Tension, 2,000 pounds.

679
00:55:06,525 --> 00:55:09,236
Very well.

680
00:55:09,320 --> 00:55:13,407
Conn, Weapons. Estimated time
to One SQ, eight minutes, 30 seconds, sir.

681
00:55:19,080 --> 00:55:21,791
The winch!

682
00:55:21,874 --> 00:55:24,502
Conn, Sonar. We have a sound short
from the buoy winch!

683
00:55:24,585 --> 00:55:26,462
Stop the goddamn winch!

684
00:55:28,089 --> 00:55:31,300
Winch is stopped, sir.

685
00:55:31,676 --> 00:55:33,052
Goddamn it.

686
00:55:45,231 --> 00:55:50,069
- TSO, is that sound still out there?
- Sonar, TSO. Is that sound still out there?

687
00:55:50,569 --> 00:55:52,613
Sound's gone, sir.

688
00:56:08,212 --> 00:56:11,424
I'm getting something.

689
00:56:16,887 --> 00:56:20,308
- Sup, he's comin' around.
- Conn, Sonar. Akula is turning toward!

690
00:56:20,391 --> 00:56:23,477
- They're range gating, sir.
- What's range gating?

691
00:56:23,561 --> 00:56:25,521
They've got the torpedoes locked on us.

692
00:56:27,315 --> 00:56:30,109
Conn, Sonar.
Torpedo in the water. Bearing 2-4-1.

693
00:56:31,694 --> 00:56:34,780
Conn, Sonar. Second torpedo
in the water. Bearing 2-4-2.

694
00:56:34,864 --> 00:56:36,699
All ahead flank.
Right full rudder.

695
00:56:42,371 --> 00:56:44,832
Conn, Sonar.
3,000 yards and closing, sir.

696
00:56:44,915 --> 00:56:46,917
Maneuvering, Conn. Cavitate.

697
00:56:53,049 --> 00:56:55,301
- Sound the collision alarm.
- Aye, sir.

698
00:56:55,384 --> 00:56:57,720
<i>- 2500 yards.
- Rig ship for impact.</i>

699
00:56:57,803 --> 00:56:59,764
Hang on to your ass, gentlemen!

700
00:56:59,805 --> 00:57:01,265
<i> 2.000 yards.</i>

701
00:57:04,226 --> 00:57:09,273
1500 yards.
Bearing 0-7-0-0-7-1.

702
00:57:09,357 --> 00:57:11,067
1,200 yards.

703
00:57:15,863 --> 00:57:18,032
1,000 yards and closing fast.

704
00:57:18,115 --> 00:57:22,787
Conn, Radio. Receiving emergency
action message. Recommend alert one.

705
00:57:22,870 --> 00:57:26,624
<i>950 yards.</i>

706
00:57:26,666 --> 00:57:29,710
Launch a five-inch evasion device.
Launch countermeasures.

707
00:57:33,965 --> 00:57:37,176
- Countermeasures away, sir.
- Shift your rudder to left full.

708
00:57:37,259 --> 00:57:39,762
<i> 500 yards and closing fast.</i>

709
00:57:44,892 --> 00:57:47,853
<i>300 yards and closing, sir.</i>

710
00:57:57,321 --> 00:58:00,241
Sir, the first torpedo's
going after the countermeasures.

711
00:58:01,993 --> 00:58:03,327
They missed! They missed!

712
00:58:04,745 --> 00:58:08,666
Sonar, Conn. Second torpedo incoming.
It's gonna be close.

713
00:58:27,101 --> 00:58:30,604
<i> Conn. Sonar.
The Akula's disappeared in the thermal.</i>

714
00:58:30,730 --> 00:58:33,107
All ahead standard.
Rudder amid ships.

715
00:58:33,190 --> 00:58:37,069
- All ahead standard. Rudder amid ships.
- All stations.

716
00:58:37,111 --> 00:58:39,905
All stations, report damage.
Report damage.

717
00:58:39,947 --> 00:58:43,409
<i> Engine room reports
number one ASW-pump failed.</i>

718
00:58:43,492 --> 00:58:48,706
<i>Torpedo room. Water in the bilge.
Request a team with a submersible pump.</i>

719
00:58:48,748 --> 00:58:53,794
<i>Engine room. Request all E-division
personnel to assist in ground isolation.</i>

720
00:58:53,878 --> 00:58:56,380
Sonar, Conn.
Report hostile contact.

721
00:58:56,881 --> 00:59:01,761
<i>- Conn. Sonar. We lost him, sir.
- Keep looking. He's looking for us.</i>

722
00:59:01,802 --> 00:59:03,012
<i>Aye, sir.</i>

723
00:59:03,095 --> 00:59:05,514
Weapons, Conn.
Estimated time to One SQ.

724
00:59:05,598 --> 00:59:09,185
Conn, Weapons. Missile systems
ready to launch in six minutes.

725
00:59:09,268 --> 00:59:10,227
<i> Very well.</i>

726
00:59:10,311 --> 00:59:12,605
<i> Main seawater pump
is out of commission.</i>

727
00:59:12,647 --> 00:59:15,650
Mr. Zimmer, where's that EAM?

728
00:59:15,733 --> 00:59:18,235
- You all right, son?
- Yes, sir.

729
00:59:20,905 --> 00:59:23,407
- That's it?
- Uh-huh. It's incomplete, sir.

730
00:59:23,449 --> 00:59:26,619
We lost it when
the radio buoy cable got severed.

731
00:59:27,119 --> 00:59:28,120
All right.

732
00:59:37,505 --> 00:59:42,885
All right, gentlemen, let's get on with it.
All ahead one-third.

733
00:59:42,969 --> 00:59:45,513
Steady as you go.

734
00:59:45,596 --> 00:59:48,641
All ahead one-third.
Steady. Aye, sir.

735
00:59:48,724 --> 00:59:51,227
Make your depth 1-5-0 feet.

736
00:59:51,310 --> 00:59:54,188
Zero bubble.
Up slow and silent to launch depth.

737
00:59:54,271 --> 00:59:58,401
Up slow and silent to launch depth.
Aye, aye, Captain.

738
01:00:00,319 --> 01:00:02,280
Captain?

739
01:00:02,363 --> 01:00:03,739
Got the EAM.

740
01:00:05,908 --> 01:00:09,120
- What do you think?
- I think there's nothing on this.

741
01:00:09,203 --> 01:00:12,123
Yes, sir.
It got cut off during the attack.

742
01:00:12,206 --> 01:00:14,875
Then it's meaningless.

743
01:00:14,959 --> 01:00:17,295
Sir, this is an EAM pertaining to nuclear...

744
01:00:17,336 --> 01:00:20,256
No, Mr. Hunter,
that's a message fragment.

745
01:00:20,923 --> 01:00:25,386
Because it got cut off during the attack, sir.
It could be a message to abort...

746
01:00:25,469 --> 01:00:29,140
- It could be a fake Russian transmission.
- Which is why we need to confirm.

747
01:00:29,432 --> 01:00:31,350
I'm asking for time to get back online.

748
01:00:31,434 --> 01:00:33,352
- Calm down, Mr. Hunter.
- I am calm.

749
01:00:33,394 --> 01:00:34,520
You don't appear to be.

750
01:00:34,603 --> 01:00:38,316
<i> Conn. Weapons. Missile systems
ready to launch in four minutes.</i>

751
01:00:38,399 --> 01:00:41,319
- Step aside, seaman.
- Yes, sir.

752
01:00:45,615 --> 01:00:50,202
We have orders in hand and those
orders are to make a preemptive launch.

753
01:00:50,286 --> 01:00:53,998
Every second we lose increases
the chances that when our missiles arrive,

754
01:00:54,081 --> 01:00:57,001
their silos could be empty
'cause they've struck us first.

755
01:00:57,043 --> 01:00:58,628
- Yes.
- You know as well as I do

756
01:00:58,711 --> 01:01:02,173
that any launch order received
without authentication is no order.

757
01:01:02,214 --> 01:01:03,758
That's our number one rule.

758
01:01:03,841 --> 01:01:07,303
That rule is the basis for the scenario
we've trained on time after time.

759
01:01:07,386 --> 01:01:09,513
It's a rule we follow without exception.

760
01:01:09,555 --> 01:01:14,268
Captain, National Military Command
Center knows what sector we're in.

761
01:01:14,393 --> 01:01:17,229
They have satellites
to see if our birds are aloft,

762
01:01:17,313 --> 01:01:20,107
and if they're not,
they give our orders to somebody else.

763
01:01:20,191 --> 01:01:22,818
That's why we maintain
more than one sub - redundancy.

764
01:01:22,902 --> 01:01:27,031
- I know about redundancy, Mr. Hunter.
- All I'm saying...

765
01:01:34,830 --> 01:01:38,334
All I'm saying, Captain,
is that we have backup.

766
01:01:38,417 --> 01:01:43,297
Now, it's our duty not to launch
until we can confirm.

767
01:01:43,381 --> 01:01:47,051
You're presuming that we have
other submarines ready to launch.

768
01:01:47,134 --> 01:01:52,014
As captain, I must assume our submarines
could've been taken out by other Akulas.

769
01:01:52,098 --> 01:01:55,810
We can play these games, but I don't have
the luxury of your presumptions.

770
01:01:55,893 --> 01:01:56,852
- Sir...
- Mr. Hunter.

771
01:01:56,936 --> 01:02:00,815
We have rules that are not open
to interpretation, personal intuition,

772
01:02:00,898 --> 01:02:04,944
gut feelings, hairs on your neck,
little devils or angels on your shoulders.

773
01:02:05,027 --> 01:02:09,073
- Captain...
- We're all very well aware of our orders.

774
01:02:09,156 --> 01:02:12,410
They come from our commander in chief.
They contain no ambiguity.

775
01:02:12,451 --> 01:02:14,829
- Captain...
- Mr. Hunter. I've made the decision.

776
01:02:14,912 --> 01:02:19,333
I'm captain of this boat.
Now shut the fuck up!

777
01:02:26,382 --> 01:02:28,426
Damn.

778
01:02:29,635 --> 01:02:30,720
Weapons, Conn.

779
01:02:30,803 --> 01:02:36,350
Shift targeting to target package
SLBM 647412/2.

780
01:02:36,434 --> 01:02:38,561
This is the captain.

781
01:02:43,399 --> 01:02:45,735
- I cannot concur.
- Repeat my command.

782
01:02:45,776 --> 01:02:49,113
We don't know what this means.
Our target could have changed.

783
01:02:49,196 --> 01:02:53,534
You repeat this order
or I'll find somebody who will!

784
01:02:53,618 --> 01:02:55,995
- You won't.
- You're relieved of your position.

785
01:02:56,120 --> 01:03:00,249
Cob, remove Mr. Hunter from the control
room. Get Lieutenant Zimmer in here!

786
01:03:00,333 --> 01:03:03,085
I do not concur.
I do not recognize your authority

787
01:03:03,127 --> 01:03:05,421
to relieve me under navy regulations.

788
01:03:05,463 --> 01:03:07,840
Cob, arrest this man
and get him out of here!

789
01:03:07,923 --> 01:03:10,593
Operating procedures governing
release of nuclear weapons

790
01:03:10,676 --> 01:03:13,638
we cannot launch our missiles
unless both you and I agree.

791
01:03:13,721 --> 01:03:15,723
Cob, what are you waiting for?

792
01:03:15,806 --> 01:03:19,435
This is why your command must be
repeated. It requires my assent.

793
01:03:19,477 --> 01:03:20,936
I do not give it.

794
01:03:20,978 --> 01:03:25,191
You continue to insist upon this launch
without confirming this message first,

795
01:03:25,316 --> 01:03:27,568
I will be backed by
the rules of precedence...

796
01:03:27,652 --> 01:03:29,904
<i>As commanding officer
of the USS Alabama.</i>

797
01:03:29,987 --> 01:03:33,908
I order you to place the XO under arrest
on the charge of mutiny!

798
01:03:33,991 --> 01:03:39,455
I say again, I order you to place the XO
under arrest on the charge of mutiny!

799
01:03:41,666 --> 01:03:43,125
Cob!

800
01:03:43,167 --> 01:03:48,130
Captain, please, the XO is right.
We can't launch unless he concurs.

801
01:03:49,674 --> 01:03:53,594
<i>"To the USS Alabama.
Rebel-controlled missiles being fueled.</i>

802
01:03:53,636 --> 01:03:57,556
"Launch codes compromised. Dissidents
threaten launch at continental US.

803
01:03:57,640 --> 01:04:01,477
Set DEFCON two. Immediately launch
ten Trident missile sorties."

804
01:04:01,560 --> 01:04:04,897
They're fueling their missiles!
We don't have time to fuck around!

805
01:04:04,981 --> 01:04:10,736
- I think you need time to think this over.
- I don't have to think this over!

806
01:04:11,737 --> 01:04:16,993
Captain, I relieve you of your command.
Cob, escort the captain to his stateroom.

807
01:04:17,034 --> 01:04:19,495
- I'm assuming command.
- You're not.

808
01:04:19,578 --> 01:04:24,625
Chief of the Boat, Captain Ramsey's
under arrest. Lock him in his stateroom.

809
01:04:24,709 --> 01:04:27,295
- Captain, please...
- Now, Cob!

810
01:04:27,378 --> 01:04:28,838
Aye, sir.

811
01:04:28,921 --> 01:04:32,633
Mitchell, Walker.
Take the captain below.

812
01:05:00,036 --> 01:05:03,247
You're way out of your league, Hunter.

813
01:05:03,331 --> 01:05:06,959
You're not ready to make
tough decisions yet.

814
01:05:20,890 --> 01:05:23,225
What the hell we waitin' for?

815
01:05:37,740 --> 01:05:41,202
Anybody here disagrees
with what I've done...

816
01:05:44,664 --> 01:05:48,709
then you feel free
to relieve yourself of duty now.

817
01:05:53,422 --> 01:05:54,966
Anybody?

818
01:06:05,351 --> 01:06:07,186
All right.

819
01:06:13,109 --> 01:06:15,361
- All stations.
- Aye, sir.

820
01:06:26,580 --> 01:06:29,750
<i> This is the executive officer.</i>

821
01:06:29,834 --> 01:06:31,877
<i>I have assumed command of this ship</i>

822
01:06:31,961 --> 01:06:36,799
<i>under authority granted me
by navy regulations.</i>

823
01:06:36,882 --> 01:06:40,386
<i>I have relieved Captain Ramsey
of his duties for acting in contravention</i>

824
01:06:40,428 --> 01:06:43,973
<i>of the rules and regulations
regarding nuclear weapons release.</i>

825
01:06:44,056 --> 01:06:48,686
<i>It is my intention
to delay the missile launch</i>

826
01:06:48,769 --> 01:06:52,398
<i>maintaining our current state of readiness</i>

827
01:06:52,523 --> 01:06:58,362
<i>pending confirmation of an emergency
action message cut off during the attack.</i>

828
01:06:58,446 --> 01:07:01,907
<i>Remain at battle stations missile.</i>

829
01:07:01,991 --> 01:07:04,076
<i>Carry on.</i>

830
01:07:06,662 --> 01:07:10,499
- What the hell are we doin', Fred?
- I'm pissin' my pants.

831
01:07:28,726 --> 01:07:30,770
Come on, boy.

832
01:07:42,198 --> 01:07:48,829
Conn, Weapons. Russians will have
missile launch capability in 39 minutes.

833
01:07:48,913 --> 01:07:50,831
Chief of the Boat.

834
01:07:54,293 --> 01:07:56,337
Sir?

835
01:07:57,588 --> 01:07:59,298
Thank you, Cob.

836
01:07:59,382 --> 01:08:02,385
"Thank you"?
Fuck you.

837
01:08:02,468 --> 01:08:05,972
Get it straight, Mr. Hunter.
I'm not on your side.

838
01:08:06,055 --> 01:08:11,102
You could be wrong. But wrong or right,
the captain can't just replace you at will.

839
01:08:11,185 --> 01:08:17,775
That was completely improper,
and that's why I did what I did, by the book.

840
01:08:17,817 --> 01:08:20,695
I thank you anyway.

841
01:08:33,040 --> 01:08:37,253
Radio, Conn. Mr. Zimmer, get those
communications back online now.

842
01:08:39,297 --> 01:08:40,798
We're working on it, sir.

843
01:08:40,881 --> 01:08:43,509
Aye, aye, Captain.

844
01:08:43,592 --> 01:08:46,220
- Are you ready?
- Uh... ready.

845
01:08:46,304 --> 01:08:47,805
Go.

846
01:08:49,015 --> 01:08:50,141
Jesus. Fuckin' thing.

847
01:08:50,224 --> 01:08:54,854
This whole system is crashed. Radio buoy
is severed. What does he want us to do?

848
01:08:54,937 --> 01:08:59,066
- Shit electrons?
- Hey, Vossler, we need communications.

849
01:08:59,191 --> 01:09:00,151
Aye, sir.

850
01:09:00,192 --> 01:09:02,820
- All stop, ten degrees up.
- Ten up. Aye, sir.

851
01:09:02,862 --> 01:09:04,864
All stop. Aye, sir. All stop.

852
01:09:25,384 --> 01:09:29,180
Conn, Sonar. Holy shit, sir!
He's on top of us! He's turning toward.

853
01:09:32,808 --> 01:09:34,810
- Range?
- 600 yards.

854
01:09:37,813 --> 01:09:42,360
Conn, Sonar. Torpedoes in the water.
Bearing 0-4-8-0-5-0.

855
01:09:44,487 --> 01:09:46,197
- Left full rudder.
- Aye, sir.

856
01:09:46,238 --> 01:09:47,782
All ahead full. Zero bubble.

857
01:09:49,700 --> 01:09:53,621
- Torpedoes are ready.
- No. Our weapons won't have time to arm.

858
01:09:53,704 --> 01:09:56,874
All ahead flank. Chief of the Watch
to Maneuvering. Max speed.

859
01:09:56,958 --> 01:09:58,209
Maximum speed.

860
01:10:04,298 --> 01:10:08,344
Sonar, Conn. Let me know when our range
to that Akula has opened to 1,000 yards.

861
01:10:08,469 --> 01:10:09,679
Aye, sir.

862
01:10:09,762 --> 01:10:12,306
Let's shoot the fucker!
What's 1,000 yards for?

863
01:10:12,390 --> 01:10:16,477
It takes 1,000 yards for the torpedoes to
arm. Who'd you fuck to get on this ship?

864
01:10:19,480 --> 01:10:23,693
Conn, Sonar. Torpedoes,
150 yards and closing fast, sir.

865
01:10:23,776 --> 01:10:28,155
Bearing 0-7-0-0-7-4.

866
01:10:29,699 --> 01:10:31,867
Launch port countermeasures.

867
01:10:34,412 --> 01:10:36,956
- Countermeasures away, sir.
- Rig ship for impact.

868
01:10:37,039 --> 01:10:38,040
Aye, sir.

869
01:10:51,095 --> 01:10:55,016
They missed! They passed astern.
They were too close to arm, sir.

870
01:10:55,099 --> 01:10:59,020
Conn, Sonar. Range to the Akula
950 yards and opening fast.

871
01:10:59,103 --> 01:11:01,522
Go to arming mechanisms,
tubes two and four.

872
01:11:04,525 --> 01:11:07,653
- Snapshot, two and four.
- Tubes fired electrically, sir.

873
01:11:17,455 --> 01:11:19,999
Give me exact ranging
and speed on our weapons.

874
01:11:20,124 --> 01:11:23,919
Range 300 yards and 50 knots, sir.

875
01:11:26,464 --> 01:11:29,175
200 yards, 50 knots.

876
01:11:31,636 --> 01:11:33,554
100 yards, 55 knots.

877
01:11:34,764 --> 01:11:37,308
75 yards.
Weapons ready for arming, sir.

878
01:11:37,391 --> 01:11:39,852
- Steady course 2-3-1.
- Aye, sir. 2-3-1.

879
01:11:40,936 --> 01:11:42,855
Arm torpedoes two and four...

880
01:11:45,066 --> 01:11:46,817
- Now.
- Torpedoes armed.

881
01:11:51,656 --> 01:11:54,450
We're locked on the Akula!

882
01:12:05,836 --> 01:12:09,423
You got him, sir! You got him!

883
01:12:17,306 --> 01:12:21,519
Conn, Sonar. Incoming torpedo. They
must have got one off before they got hit.

884
01:12:21,644 --> 01:12:25,189
Right full rudder.
Launch starboard countermeasures.

885
01:12:25,314 --> 01:12:27,775
- Countermeasures away.
- Dive, depth 1200 feet.

886
01:12:27,817 --> 01:12:32,113
Down now. Take her deep, take her deep.
Full dive on those planes. Let's go!

887
01:12:34,490 --> 01:12:36,450
Hang on, everybody!

888
01:13:07,440 --> 01:13:10,693
- Is everybody OK?
- Yeah!

889
01:13:16,991 --> 01:13:20,036
Open the aft main drain suction!

890
01:13:20,119 --> 01:13:23,289
Start the drain pump!
Go, go, go!

891
01:13:27,001 --> 01:13:30,129
All stations,
make damage report to Control.

892
01:13:30,212 --> 01:13:35,176
Control, this is Bilge Bay.
We've got out-of-control flooding.

893
01:13:35,217 --> 01:13:37,178
Request damage control.

894
01:13:37,219 --> 01:13:40,723
- Get a damage control party down there.
- Aye, sir.

895
01:13:40,806 --> 01:13:44,977
Get Lieutenant Hellerman. Flooding
in the bilge bay. Get him down there now!

896
01:13:50,149 --> 01:13:52,944
Conn, Maneuvering.
We've lost propulsion, sir.

897
01:13:53,027 --> 01:13:56,739
- Chief of the Boat, how we doin'?
- We are going down. I need propulsion.

898
01:13:56,822 --> 01:14:01,327
Forward ballast tanks are damaged, sir.
Forward air pressure, zero.

899
01:14:01,827 --> 01:14:05,081
Maneuvering, Conn.
Restore propulsion as soon as possible.

900
01:14:05,206 --> 01:14:08,751
Restoring propulsion
as soon as possible. Aye, sir.

901
01:14:22,390 --> 01:14:27,520
Control, Bilge Bay. Flooding is slowed.
I think we got it under control, sir.

902
01:14:27,561 --> 01:14:32,066
Passing 1500 feet.
At 1850, it's all over.

903
01:14:48,582 --> 01:14:50,251
Passing 1600 feet.

904
01:15:02,263 --> 01:15:05,433
Barnes, get over here.
Help me with this loose valve!

905
01:15:18,571 --> 01:15:21,449
Passing 1650 feet.

906
01:15:30,291 --> 01:15:34,211
- What the fuck is going on?
- Take it easy.

907
01:15:45,931 --> 01:15:50,770
Conn, Bilge Bay. Flooding has
recommenced. Three men are trapped.

908
01:15:51,604 --> 01:15:55,107
Bilge Bay, Conn. Try and get those men
out of there and seal that bay.

909
01:15:55,191 --> 01:15:59,320
Sir, if we don't seal the bilge bay now,
we'll lose the ship.

910
01:16:00,780 --> 01:16:03,824
Bilge Bay, Conn.
Can you get the men out?

911
01:16:03,908 --> 01:16:06,911
There's no way.
If I go down there, I'll never get out.

912
01:16:08,955 --> 01:16:12,750
Barnes, come on!
You've got to come! Move, move!

913
01:16:12,833 --> 01:16:15,962
<i>Barnes, come on!
You can do it! Move it!</i>

914
01:16:16,712 --> 01:16:18,756
Bilge Bay, Conn.
Seal that bay.

915
01:16:18,839 --> 01:16:21,676
Barnes, let's go! Come on!
I've got to close the hatch!

916
01:16:23,844 --> 01:16:27,264
What the fuck are we doing here?

917
01:16:27,306 --> 01:16:29,934
Bilge Bay, Conn.
I say again, seal that bay.

918
01:16:30,017 --> 01:16:32,687
Sir, there are men down there.
They're gonna drown.

919
01:16:32,770 --> 01:16:35,564
Lieutenant Hellerman,
you have your orders.

920
01:16:35,648 --> 01:16:38,442
Now seal the goddamn bay
